<Layout title="Module 7 – Medication Administration">
  <h1>Module 7: Medication Administration</h1>
  <p>
    Safe medication administration is one of the nurse's most critical responsibilities.
    Errors in this area can cause serious patient harm. Applying the rights of medication
    administration and using available safety resources dramatically reduce the risk of errors.
  </p>

  <h2>Rights of Medication Administration</h2>
  <p>The classic <strong>5 Rights</strong> have been expanded to 10 in modern practice:</p>
  <ol>
    <li><strong>Right Patient</strong> — Use 2 identifiers (name + DOB or MRN).</li>
    <li><strong>Right Medication</strong> — Compare MAR to medication label three times.</li>
    <li><strong>Right Dose</strong> — Calculate and verify; question unusual doses.</li>
    <li><strong>Right Route</strong> — Confirm route is appropriate and ordered.</li>
    <li><strong>Right Time</strong> — Administer within 30–60 min of scheduled time per facility policy.</li>
    <li><strong>Right Documentation</strong> — Document immediately after administration.</li>
    <li><strong>Right Reason</strong> — Understand the indication for the medication.</li>
    <li><strong>Right Response</strong> — Assess for therapeutic and adverse effects.</li>
    <li><strong>Right Education</strong> — Teach the patient about their medication.</li>
    <li><strong>Right to Refuse</strong> — Respect the patient's right to refuse; document and notify provider.</li>
  </ol>
  <div class="warning">
    <strong>⚠️ Triple Check</strong>
    Compare the medication label to the MAR:
    (1) when retrieving from storage,
    (2) when preparing the dose, and
    (3) before administering to the patient.
  </div>

  <h2>Medication Routes</h2>
  <table>
    <thead>
      <tr><th>Route</th><th>Abbreviation</th><th>Notes</th></tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr><td>Oral</td><td>PO</td><td>Most common; assess swallowing ability; never crush enteric-coated or extended-release tablets</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Sublingual</td><td>SL</td><td>Under the tongue; rapid absorption (e.g., nitroglycerin); do not swallow</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Buccal</td><td>—</td><td>Between gum and cheek; slow, sustained absorption</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Topical</td><td>Top</td><td>Applied to skin; wear gloves; rotate sites (e.g., nitroglycerin paste)</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Transdermal</td><td>TD</td><td>Patch; remove old patch before applying new one; rotate sites</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Inhaled</td><td>INH</td><td>MDI, DPI, nebulizer; teach proper technique; rinse mouth after corticosteroids</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Optic / Otic / Nasal</td><td>—</td><td>Administer per specific technique; warm ear drops to body temp</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Subcutaneous</td><td>SQ/SC</td><td>45–90° angle; rotate sites; insulin, heparin</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Intramuscular</td><td>IM</td><td>90° angle; select site based on medication volume and patient</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Intravenous</td><td>IV</td><td>Fastest absorption; highest risk; see Module 8</td></tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>

  <h2>Injection Technique</h2>
  <h3>Subcutaneous (SQ) Injections</h3>
  <ul>
    <li>Volume: ≤ 1 mL; use 25–27 gauge, 5/8-inch needle.</li>
    <li>Sites: Abdomen (avoid 2-inch radius around umbilicus), outer thigh, upper arm.</li>
    <li>Angle: 45° if limited subcutaneous tissue; 90° if adequate tissue.</li>
    <li>Aspirate: <em>Not</em> recommended for insulin or heparin injections.</li>
  </ul>
  <h3>Intramuscular (IM) Injections</h3>
  <table>
    <thead>
      <tr><th>Site</th><th>Max Volume</th><th>Preferred For</th></tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr><td>Ventrogluteal</td><td>3–5 mL (adult)</td><td>Preferred in adults; fewest vessels and nerves</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Vastus lateralis (thigh)</td><td>1–3 mL</td><td>Infants, children, adults with limited gluteal mass</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Deltoid</td><td>≤ 1 mL</td><td>Vaccines in adults; small volumes only</td></tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>
  <ul>
    <li>Use 21–23 gauge, 1–1.5-inch needle for most adult IM injections.</li>
    <li>Use Z-track technique to prevent medication leakage into subcutaneous tissue.</li>
    <li>Aspirate: Not routinely recommended for most IM sites (CDC guideline for vaccines).</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>High-Alert Medications</h2>
  <p>
    High-alert medications have a narrow safety margin; errors can cause significant harm.
    Always require independent double-check per facility policy.
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li>Insulin (hypoglycemia risk)</li>
    <li>Anticoagulants: Heparin, warfarin, direct oral anticoagulants (bleeding risk)</li>
    <li>Opioids (respiratory depression)</li>
    <li>Concentrated electrolytes: KCl, hypertonic saline (cardiac arrest risk)</li>
    <li>Chemotherapy agents</li>
    <li>Neuromuscular blocking agents</li>
  </ul>
  <div class="note">
    <strong>📌 ISMP</strong>
    The Institute for Safe Medication Practices (ISMP) publishes and updates the high-alert
    medication list. Familiarize yourself with your facility's list and required safety checks.
  </div>

  <h2>Medication Calculations Review</h2>
  <h3>Desired Over Available Formula</h3>
  <p><strong>Dose to Administer = (Desired Dose ÷ Available Dose) × Quantity</strong></p>
  <p>
    <em>Example:</em> Order: furosemide 60 mg PO. Available: furosemide 40 mg/tablet.<br />
    Dose = (60 ÷ 40) × 1 tablet = 1.5 tablets
  </p>
  <h3>Weight-Based Calculations</h3>
  <p>
    <em>Example:</em> Order: amoxicillin 25 mg/kg/day PO divided q8h. Patient weight: 20 kg.<br />
    Daily dose = 25 × 20 = 500 mg/day.<br />
    Per dose = 500 ÷ 3 = 166.7 mg ≈ 167 mg per dose.
  </p>

  <h2>Key Terms</h2>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>MAR:</strong> Medication Administration Record — the legal record of all medications administered.</li>
    <li><strong>ISMP:</strong> Institute for Safe Medication Practices.</li>
    <li><strong>PRN:</strong> Pro re nata — as needed.</li>
    <li><strong>STAT:</strong> Immediately.</li>
    <li><strong>Z-track technique:</strong> IM injection method that displaces the skin to seal medication in the muscle tissue.</li>
    <li><strong>Enteric-coated:</strong> Tablet coating that prevents dissolution in the stomach; never crush.</li>
  </ul>
</Layout>
